# Project Development Guidelines

## Code Quality
- Write all code with readability as the highest priority.
- Minimize duplicate code and extract reusable functions or classes.
- Ensure every function and method follows the Single Responsibility Principle.
- Use clear and meaningful names for variables and functions.
- Extract hard-coded values into constants.

## Code Style
- Maintain consistent coding conventions throughout the project.
- Use 2 spaces for indentation.
- Keep each line under 80 characters whenever possible.
- Follow naming conventions for classes, functions, and variables.
- Comments should explain why the code is written that way,
  not just what it does.

## Documentation
- Write documentation comments for all public APIs.
- Describe project setup and execution steps clearly in the README.
- Document complex algorithms or business logic in separate documents.
- Record all changes in the CHANGELOG.

## Testing
- Write unit tests for all new features.
- Maintain at least 80% test coverage.
- Ensure tests are independent and repeatable.
- Implement integration tests for critical user flows.

## Security
- Always validate and sanitize user input.
- Store sensitive data in environment variables or secure storage.
- Regularly check external libraries for security vulnerabilities.
- Prevent common vulnerabilities such as SQL Injection and XSS.

## Performance
- Optimize database queries.
- Minimize unnecessary API calls.
- Apply pagination for large datasets.
- Handle resource-intensive tasks asynchronously.

## Version Control
- Write clear and descriptive commit messages.
- Develop features in separate branches.
- Conduct code reviews before merging pull requests.
- Keep the main branch always deployable.

## Project Structure
- Organize packages based on a layered architecture.
- Each package should have a single responsibility.
- Circular dependencies are strictly prohibited.
- Follow Domain-Driven Design principles where applicable.

# React Project Structure (UCEO)

src/
├── assets/       # Static resources such as images and fonts
├── components/   # Reusable components
│  ├── common/    # Shared components
│  ├── layout/    # Layout components
│  └── features/  # Feature-specific components
├── hooks/        # Custom hooks
├── pages/        # Page components
├── services/     # API communication logic
├── store/        # State management (Redux, Recoil, etc.)
├── styles/       # Global styles and theme configuration
├── types/        # TypeScript type definitions
├── utils/        # Utility functions
└── constants/    # Constants

public/
├── index.html
└── static/       # Static files

# Main Directory Description

components/
- Reusable UI components
  - common/: Shared components such as buttons and inputs
  - layout/: Layout elements like header, footer, sidebar
  - features/: Components tied to specific features

hooks/
- Collection of custom hooks

pages/
- Page components mapped to routes

services/
- API communication and external service integrations

store/
- Global state management logic

styles/
- Global styles, themes, and styling utilities

types/
- TypeScript interfaces and type definitions

utils/
- Utility and helper functions

constants/
- Constants and configuration values

# Naming Conventions

Component files:
PascalCase.tsx
Example: Button.tsx

Hook files:
camelCase.ts
Example: useAuth.ts

Utility files:
camelCase.ts
Example: formatDate.ts

Style files:
camelCase.module.css
Example: button.module.css

Test files:
*.test.tsx
*.spec.tsx

# Component Structure

components/
└── ComponentName/
    ├── index.tsx
    ├── ComponentName.module.css
    ├── ComponentName.test.tsx
    └── types.ts

index.tsx → Main component  
ComponentName.module.css → Component styles  
ComponentName.test.tsx → Unit tests  
types.ts → Type definitions
